scipline, defined by bureaucratized institutions as the inability to work. By interrogating the representational effort necessary to make work seem inherently meaningful, Carmody ultimately reveals a forgotten history of competing efforts to think social belonging beyond or even without work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionszUnited States. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aMinoritiesxSocial conditionszUnited States. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxSocial conditionszUnited States. 0aPeople with disabilitieszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aPublic welfarexHistoryzUnited States. 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWelfare recipientsxHistoryzUnited States. 0aWelfare recipientszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWorkxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478092834?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478092834zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478092834/original  a978-3-11-076691-2 Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA